Certainly! Below is an example of how to generate a parallelogram in \(\mathbb{R}^2\) using TikZ, which is formed by two linearly independent vectors. The same concept can be extended to a parallelepiped in \(\mathbb{R}^3\).

### Parallelogram in \(\mathbb{R}^2\)

```latex
\documentclass[tikz,border=10pt]{standalone}
\begin{document}

% Define the vectors
\def\a{(2, 1)}
\def\b{(1, 3)}

% Draw the parallelogram
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1]
    % Start at the origin (0,0)
    \coordinate (O) at (0,0);

    % Draw vector \a from O
    \draw[->, thick] (O) -- ++\a node[midway, above right] {$\vec{a}$};

    % Draw vector \b from O
    \draw[->, thick] (O) -- ++\b node[midway, above left] {$\vec{b}$};

    % Draw the other two sides of the parallelogram
    \draw[thick] ++\a -- ++\b;
    \draw[thick] ++(0,0) -- ++\b;

    % Label the vertices
    \node at (\a) [right] {A};
    \node at (\b) [above left] {B};
    \node at ($(O)+\a+\b$) [below right] {C};
    \node at (O) [left] {D};
\end{tikzpicture}

\end{document}
```

### Explanation:
- **Vectors**: The vectors \(\vec{a}\) and \(\vec{b}\) are defined as `(2, 1)` and `(1, 3)` respectively.
- **Drawing Vectors**: The `\draw[->, thick]` command draws the vectors from the origin `(0,0)` to their respective points.
- **Completing the Parallelogram**: The other two sides of the parallelogram are drawn by extending the lines from the endpoints of the vectors.
- **Labels**: Labels for the vertices are added for clarity.

